Rust concurrency explained simply 👇

```rust
pub type AppState = Arc<RwLock<HashMap<i32, Todo>>>;
```

This single line gives you a:

✅ Thread-safe
✅ Shared
✅ In-memory database
for your Axum API.

Why all this complexity?

Because your backend handles:

* multiple requests
* multiple threads
* concurrent access

Without protection, two requests could modify the `HashMap` at the same time → 💥 data races & memory corruption.

Here’s the magic:

🔹 `HashMap`
Stores your todos in memory.

🔹 `RwLock`
Allows:

* many readers at once 👀
* only one writer at a time ✍️

Perfect for APIs because reads happen more than writes.

🔹 `Arc`
Lets multiple handlers safely share the same state across threads.

Visualize it like this:

```text
Arc
 └── RwLock
      └── HashMap
           ├── 1 -> Todo
           ├── 2 -> Todo
           └── 3 -> Todo
```

Real-world analogy 🏠

* `HashMap` = cupboard storing todos
* `RwLock` = security system
* `Arc` = duplicate room keys

Many people can LOOK 👀
Only one can CHANGE ✍️

Rust makes backend concurrency feel safe by design 🦀
